occurrences.line_text: Long way he trauelled, before he heard of ought.
At length they chaunst to meet vpon the way
And all the way he prayed, as he went,
(Quoth then that aged man;) the way to win
He making speedy way through spersed ayre,
The God obayde, and calling forth straight way
At last him chaunst to meete vpon the way
He had a faire companion of his way,
She intertainde her louer all the way:
The red bloud trickling staind the way, as he did ride.
Till weary of their way, they came at last,
One day nigh wearie of the yrkesome way,
Shamefully at her rayling all the way,
Might fall on her, and follow all the way,
And in the way as she did weepe and waile,
So forth they past, and all the way they spent
And all the way, with great lamenting paine,
And all the way she wets with flowing teares:
And towards it a broad high way that led,
For she is wearie of the toilesome way,
He leaues the welkin way most beaten plaine,
To Ioues high house through heauens bras-paued way
When such an one had guiding of the way,
And all the way, most like a brutish beast,
Showting for ioy, and still before their way
Which when the wakeful Elfe perceiu'd, streight way
Through widest ayre making his ydle way,
But to the easterne coast of heauen makes speedy way.
Through mirkesome aire her readie way she makes.
By that same way the direfull dames doe driue
And backe returning tooke her wonted way,
Scarse could he footing find in that fowle way,
Where none appeares can make her selfe a way:
A wondrous way it for this Lady wrought,
And all the way their merry pipes they sound,
And chaunst vnwares to meet him in the way,
A wearie wight forwandring by the way,
And soild with dust of the long dried way;
To see two knights in trauell on my way
He had not trauaild long, when on the way
All as the Dwarfe the way to her assynd:
A goodly knight, faire marching by the way
The idle stroke, enforcing furious way,
The fierce threeforked engin making way,
That stop out of the way to ouerthroe,
And with his bodie bard the way atwixt them twaine.
Both feet and face one way are wont to lead.
Then asked he, which way he in might pas:
Thus beene they parted, Arthur on his way
As on the way together we did fare,
A wide way made to let forth liuing breath.
Who trauels by the wearie wandring way,
For he, that once hath missed the right way,
the way to heauenly blesse.
The Porter opened vnto them streight way:
For streight & narrow was the way, which he did show.
What grace hath thee now hither brought this way?
All keepe the broad high way, and take delight
Then with a few to walke the rightest way;
And this good knight his way with me addrest,
Her stedfast eyes were bent, ne swarued other way.
Forth from her presence, by a narrow way,
That was fore by the way, she did him bring,
That by the wearie way were traueiling,
Thence forward by that painfull way they pas,
Is not from hence the way, that leadeth right
And shewes the way, his sinfull soule to saue.
Who better can the way to heauen aread,
Then come thou man of earth, and see the way,
Or streight way on that last long voyage fare,
To walke this way in Pilgrims poore estate.
As he his toylesome teme that way did guyde,
And taught the way that does to heauen bound?
Is gathered full, and worketh speedy way:
To beare so great a weight: he cutting way
And made such way, that hewd it quite in twaine;
There this faire virgin wearie of her way
And made delightfull musicke all the way,
And all the way the ioyous people sings,
Out of my way, through perils straunge and hard;
And priuie spials plast in all his way,
Vpon the way him fortuned to meet,
Him als accompanyd vpon the way
Least his long way his aged limbes should tire:
So now he Guyon guides an vncouth way
But when he heard him speake, streight way he knew
And with his steedie staffe did point his way:
Dan Faunus chaunst to meet her by the way,
Meetes two contrary billowes by the way,
She scorning both their spights, does make wide way,
The whiles a losell wandring by the way,
And by the way he chaunced to espy
But easie is the way, and passage plaine
Would from the right way seeke to draw him wide,
It fortuned forth faring on his way,
And chawing vengeance all the way I went,
Whose flying feet so fast their way applyde,
That when the varlet heard and saw, streight way
On which it seizing, no way enter might,
And euery way did seeke into his life,
The wearie Traueiler, wandring that way,
And lightly mounted, passeth on his way,
She in receiu'd; but Atin by no way
For it was taught the way, which she would haue,
And all the way, the wanton Damzell found
About her litle frigot, therein making way.
That of his way he had no souenaunce,
Diuerse discourses in their way they spent,
Disburdned her. Their way they forward take
And by the way, as was her wonted guize,
Me litle needed from my right way to haue straid.
Who fares on sea, may not commaund his way,
And in the way he with Sir Guyon met,
In his owne flesh, and make way to the liuing spright.
Yet on his way, of none accompanide;
A darkesome way, which no man could descry,
Through which a beaten broad high way did trace,
But th'Elfin knight with wonder all the way
To him did open, and affoorded way;
Soone as he entred was, the dore streight way
Him to entrap vnwares another way he wist.
They neuer creature saw, that came that way.
But he was warie wise in all his way,
And being on his way, approched neare,
Yet since no way is left to wreake my spight,
Which hewing quite a sunder, further way
To yield wide way to his hart-thrilling brond;
Forth passed on their way in faire accord,
But in her way throwes mischiefe and mischaunce,
But constant keepe the way, in which ye stand;
They wasted had much way, and measurd many miles.
Till that the venturous Mariner that way
Who him at first well vsed euery way;
By which he freed the Traueilers high way,
Through hils and dales he speedie way did make,
Some land-marke seem'd to be, or signe of sundry way.
And led him to the Castle by the beaten way.
And keepe an euen course; for yonder way
Till that Latona traueiling that way,
And passe on forward: so their way does ly,
But by the way, there is a great Quicksand,
For twixt them both the narrow way doth ly.
Did couet, as they passed by that way,
How to direct their way in darkenesse wide,
Yet swarued not, but kept their forward way,
The way they came, the same retourn'd they right,
Streight way he with his vertuous staffe them strooke,
Because of trauell long, a nigher way,
But he him selfe betooke another way,
But stoutly dealt his blowes, and euery way
That euery knight, which doth this way repaire,
To which sharpe thornes and breres the way forstall,
Way to her loue, and secret darts did throw;
She trauelling with Guyon by the way,
But went her way; ne her vnguilty age
Streight way with dreames, and with fantasticke sight
They both vprose and tooke their readie way
Of name Cayr-Merdin cald, they tooke their way:
And if thou euer happen that same way
Way for themselues, their purpose to partake?
Ne euer dofte her armes, but all the way
By this forbidden way in my despight,
But forward rode, and kept her readie way
As he by chaunce did wander that same way,
At last they came vnto a double way,
To take that way, in which that Damozell
Of the wide aire her way does cut amaine,
Who lately left the same, and tooke this way:
Which way she fared hath, good Sir tell out of hand.
Or succour her, or me direct the way;
But by the way he greatly gan complaine
By that same way they knew that Squire vnknowne
The gentle Squire came ryding that same way,
At last through wrath and vengeaunce making way,
And doth for wretched mens reliefe make way;
And searched euery way, through which his wings
A traueller vnwonted to such way:
To passe that way, as forth he trauelled;
And all the way him followd on the strand,
Thus as he led the Beast along the way,
And crost the nearest way, by which he cast
But she the way shund nathemore for thy,
Him needed not instruct, which way were best
A knight that way there chaunced to repaire;
There them by chaunce encountred on the way
And said, his boat the way could wisely tell:
To his first way. And as they forward went,
Yet will I not forsake my forward way,
By such close signes they secret way did make
Yet warily he watcheth euery way,
For I vnwares this way by fortune straid,
Through many a wood, and many an vncouth way,
As on aduenture by the way he past:
But went his way; whom when he passed kend,
Before ye enterprise that way to wend:
Did all the way him follow hard behind,
And bad the stubborne flames to yield him way:
And nicely trode, as thornes lay in his way,
Forgetfull of his safety, hath his right way lost.
Tho blinding him againe, his way he forth did take.
So soone as they were in, the dore streight way
By way of sport, as oft in maskes is knowen,
And now she is with her vpon the way,
Till on his way they had him forth conuayd:
And all the way with wondrous griefe of mynd,
By great aduenture trauelled that way;
And there arresting, readie way did yield,
That making way vnto his dearest life,
Resolu'd to end it one or other way;
And so gaue way vnto his fell intent:
Yet still that direfull stroke kept on his way,
Which straight flew ope, and gaue her way to ride.
As was his wont; so weening way to make
And strange aduentures, all the way they rode:
And pleasaunt bord, they past forth on their way,
The next day, as he on his way did ride,
When euer he this way shall passe by day or night.
And yeeld vnto her weapon way to pas:
We trauelled, both wearie of the way
In all which time, Sir Artegall made way
Forth on his way, to which he was ybent.
Ne wight him to attend, or way to guide,
And by the way she sundry purpose found
Both of the way, and warlike exercise,
Ran, till he came to th'end of all his way,
For she deare Ladie all the way was dead,
Doth hast to crosse him by the nearest way,
His owne deare Lord Prince Arthure came that way,
And looking after long, did marke which way she straid.
How all the way the Prince on footpace traced,
They passing forth kept on their readie way,
And all the way from trotting hard to spare,
That all the way full loud for aide did crie,
He all the way did rage at that same Squire,
Whose will her weakenesse could no way represse,
And seeking long, to weet which way she straid
That as we ride together on our way,
But by one way, that passage did prepare.
But by no meanes my way I would forslow,
Past forth on foote, beholding all the way
He gan forthwith t'auale, and way vnto me yield.
And all the way before them as they went,
And almost blind through eld, that scarce her way could see.
When to Ioues pallace she doth take her way;
The wanton Lee, that oft doth loose his way,
His way still vnder ground, till Thamis he ouertake.
The first, the gentle Shure that making way
The Doune & eke the Frith, both which prepard her way.
By one or other way me woefull thrall,
But all in vaine: for why he found no way
Did march amongst the many all the way:
And all the way did inly mourne, like one astray.
Did to the Faery Queene her way addresse,
And now together on their way they bin,
Aread (sayd he) which way then did he make?
To which as he now was vppon the way,
And finding in the way the scattred scarfe,
But in my way a little here beyond
For neuer wight he lets to passe that way,
None other way will I this day betake,
But thitherward forthright his ready way did make.
He saw no way, but close with him in hast;
Which way he enter might, without endangerment.
And made way for his maister to assaile.
In which they measur'd mickle weary way,
Within his ballaunce, he could way aright.
And swat, and chauf'd, and proued euery way:
But rather stroue extremities to way,
Ne any of them durst come in his way,
Vpon the way, with that his snowy Dame.
Streight way so soone as both together met,
And to my brother did ellope streight way:
But suffred cruell shipwracke by the way.
Departed on his way, as did befall,
So as he trauelled vppon the way,
And nimbly did him dight to guide the way
And to them way to make, with weapons well prepard.
But in the middle way they were ymet
But tossed in her troublous minde, what way
Vnto the wall his way did fearelesse take,
And thenceforth vnto daunger opened way.
To which if thou canst win him any way,
And to his fortunes helpe make readie way?
Towards which coast her loue his way addrest.
So forth she rode vppon her ready way,
They seeing that, let driue at him streight way,
Gan her addresse vnto her former way.
The way to her, and those two losels scared.
She stayd not to aduise which way to take;
Thorough the midst of them she way did make.
That way betwixt them none appeares in sight;
Went on his way, ne euer howre did cease,
The true guide of his way and vertuous gouernment.
How euer loth he were his way to slake,
Continu'd still his course, and by the way
As by the way vnweetingly I strayd,
To treat with her by way of enterdeale,
To their deseigne to make the easier way,
And sent to him a Page, that mote direct his way.
Gaue way vnto his horses speedie flying,
Seeking by euery way to make some breach,
But go, which way they list, their guide they haue forlore.
With vgly craples crawling in their way,
And so would haue departed on their way.
Agree to goe with her, and by the way,
And by which way they towards it should trace.
She gladly graunted it: then he straight way
Vnto his way, which now was all his care and count.
And all his way before him still prepare.
Ne to their force gaue way, that was great wonder,
Thenceforth he car'd no more, which way he strooke,
Which being shew'd, he gan him selfe streight way
And sure he had her slaine, had she not turnd her way.
And for her entrailes made an open way,
On which long way he rode, ne euer day did rest.
Who hauing left Mercilla, streight way went
Through many perils and much way did pas,
There as he traueld by the way, he met
Tho as they rode together on their way,
To the sea shore he gan his way apply,
That through the yron walles their way they rent,
And way did giue vnto their gracelesse speed:
And Talus to reuoke from the right way,
By the way side being together set,
That all the woods and rockes nigh to that way,
From his right course, but still the way did hold
And now he was in trauell on his way,
That way, (and yet they needs must passe that way),
That way, (and yet they needs must passe that way),
He this same day, as I that way did come
Of one loud crying, which they streight way ghest,
Breakes forth, and makes his way more violent.
The Dwarfe his way did hast, and went all night;
His Helme, to make vnto his vengeance way.
He now againe is on his former way,
That he streight way with haughtie choler burned,
Vpon our way, to which we weren bent,
And needeth safegard now vpon her way,
Gan freshly him addresse vnto his former way.
So as they past together on their way,
Ne wist which way he through the foord mote pas.
Turned his steede about another way,
The groome went streight way in, and to his Lord
He stayed not t'aduize, which way were best
And euery way did try, but all in vaine:
And furie, to be crossed in his way,
To weet which way were best to entertaine,
Which way to take: now West he went a while,
Vpon a day as on their way they went,
She on her way cast forward to proceede,
And all the way the Prince sought to appease
To passe the tedious trauell of the way;
They stayd not there, but streight way in did pas.
To tend them well. So forth he went his way,
And went both on their way, ne ech would other leaue.
To some hid end to make more easie way,
So vp he rose, and forth streight way he went
So as they rode, he saw the way all dyde
Was wandred in the wood another way,
And now she was vppon the weary way,
And all the way he went, on euery syde
And past through many perils by the way,
So as they forward on their way did pas,
The Prince assented, and then he streight way
But with his yron club preparing way,
So as he could not weld him any way.
That he which way to turne him scarcely wist:
That way to them he gaue forth right to pas.
But being checkt, he did abstaine streight way,
They towards euening wandring euery way,
And drawing thence his speach another way,
And cleane were gone, which way he neuer knew;
As he this way comming from feastfull glee,
Couered with shrubby woods, in which no way
For vnderneath the ground their way was made,
But making way for death at large to walke:
About some carcase by the common way,
The readie way vnto that theeuish wonne,
To whom they both agreed to take their way,
Through the dead carcases he made his way;
Till he had strowd with bodies all the way;
Still winneth way, ne hath her compasse lost:
Right so it fares with me in this long way,
Which she streight way for dread least, if her syre
And though they faultie were, yet well he wayd,
Full many things so doubtfull to be wayd,
That on a time as they together way'd,
But if the one be with the other wayd,
For by no meanes the false will with the truth be wayd.
But wander too and fro in wayes vnknowne,
In wayes vnknowne, her wandring knight to seeke,
And thousand other wayes, to bait his fleshly hookes.
Vnweeting of the perillous wandring wayes,
First made by him, mens wandring wayes to guyde,
They let her goe at will, and wander wayes vnknowne.
That rules mens wayes, and rules the thoughts of liuing wight.
Me hither brought by wayes yet neuer found,
Greeu'd with remembrance of his wicked wayes,
In all his wayes through this wide worldes waue,
The face of earth, and wayes of liuing wight,
And guide thy wayes with warie gouernaunce,
By that wayes side, there sate infernall Payne,
And all by wrong wayes for themselues prepard.
Were fixed at his backe, to cut his ayerie wayes.
By secret wayes, that none might it espy,
Whom he at sea found wandring from their wayes,
The other fiue, fiue sundry wayes he set,
For thy he gan some other wayes aduize,
After long wayes and perilous paines endured,
Long so they trauelled through wastefull wayes,
Full many wayes within her troubled mind,
Therefore submit thy wayes vnto his will,
What meanes shall she out seeke, or what wayes take?
And through back wayes, that none might them espy,
At last their wayes so fell, that they mote part
So beene they three three sundry wayes ybent.
Tho when her wayes he could no more descry,
For day discouers all dishonest wayes,
His late miswandred wayes now to remeasure right.
All wayes she sought, him to restore to plight,
Ten thousand wayes he cast in his confused thought.
With squinted eyes contrarie wayes intended,
The doubtfull current into diuers wayes:
And euery secret worke of natures wayes,
By wondrous skill, and many hidden wayes,
And all the wayes she sought, his loue for to haue wonne.
And hidden wayes, that scarse an hound by smell
Handling and turning them a thousand wayes.
He knew the diuerse went of mortall wayes,
For well she knew the wayes to win good will
To worke by wicked treason wayes doth find,
An aged wight, wayfaring all alone,
And when they both had wept and wayld their fill,
Nor wayld of friends, nor laid on groning beare,
Of one, that wayld and pittifull[y] wept,
He wept, and wayld, and false laments belyde,
The whyles she wayld, the more they did reioyce.
To wayle his woefull case she would not stay,
That nought she did but wayle, and often steepe
But that she still did waste, and still did wayle,
And Canacee gan wayle her dearest frend.
And all the wooddy Nymphes did wayle and mourne.
Gan weepe and wayle, as if great griefe had her affected.
Or who did wayle or watch the wearie night?
What now is left her, but to wayle and weepe,
Of caytiue wretched thrals, that wayled night and day.
In waylfull plaints, that none was to appease;
Doest thou sit wayling by black Stygian lake,
Wayling, and raysing pittifull vprore,
For what bootes it to weepe and to wayment,
She made so piteous mone and deare wayment,
That did presume his fathers firie wayne,
May seeme the wayne was very euill led,
The Sunnes bright wayne to Phaetons decay,
Amendment readie still at hand did wayt,
That dreadfull feend, which did behind him wayt,
Vpon Ioues iudgement seat wayt day and night,
But wayt on him in euery place and part.
But wayt aduantage, when they downe did light.
Which there did wayte, willing them forth to call
They wayted, that the night was forward spent,
Long wayted, saw his sudden desolation,
For whom they wayted as his mortall fone,
And that wilde Champion wayting her besyde:
And one sate wayting euer them before,
The watchman wayting tydings glad to heare,
Wayting to passe, he saw whereas did swim
Wayting when as the Antheme should be sung on hye.
Wayting, how Fortune would resolue that daungerous dout.
Like to a Spaniell wayting carefully
Wayting what would ensue of that euent.
Wayting what end would be of that same daunger drad.
With onely Talus wayting diligent,
Wayting his foe, it did her dead hart cheare,
There wayting for the Tyrant, till it was farre day.
Wayting if he vnwares him murther might:
Wayting what tydings of her folke became.
Like as a wayward childe, whose sounder sleepe
Banisht from liuing wights, our wearie dayes we waste.
We may not chaunge (quoth he) this euil plight,
Till we be bathed in a liuing well;
O helpe Orgoglio, helpe, or else we perish all.
As on the way together we did fare,
We met that villen (God from him me blesse)
The author of this fact, we here behold,
If any strength we haue, it is to ill,
All is but lost, that liuing we bestow,
All in his hand, euen dead we honour should.
Now are we come vnto my natiue soyle,
For we be come vnto a quiet rode,
Where we must land some of our passengers,
Which we farre off will here abide to vew.
But wretched we, where ye haue left your marke,
So parted we and on our iourney driue,
That we may pitty such vnhappy bale,
Our selues in league of vowed loue we knit:
In which we long time without gealous feares,
Here may ye not haue entraunce, though we would:
We would and would againe, if that we could;
We would and would againe, if that we could;
